column168: SHIPMENT OF FIVE (5) DRUMS LOADED AT FACILITY IN CINCINATTI OHIO TO BE SENT TO FACILITY IN ATLANTA GEORGIA. DRUMS LOADED ATOP CARDBOARD TO PREVENT DRUM FATIGUE. PROTRUDING NAIL IN THE FLOOR CAUSED SMALL PUNCTURE IN ONE (1) DRUM. CONTENTS STARTED LEAKING AND WERE ABSORBED BY CARDBOARD UNTIL SATURATED. LEAK WAS DETECTED BY DRIVER THAT WAS CONDUCTING PRE TRIP TRAILER INSPECTION. DRIVER NOTIFIED FREIGHT OPERATIONS SUPERVISOR OF THE LEAK. INDIVIDUALS ENTERED INTO THE TRAILER AND STARTED TO MOVE DRUMS TO DETECT THE LEAKING DRUM. THE PUNCTURED DRUM WAS FOUND AND TURNED UP SIDE DOWN TO PREVENT MORE LEAKAGE. THE DRIVER LATER COMPLAINED OF LIGHT HEADNESS AND WAS TRANSPORTED TO THE LOCAL HOSPITAL WHERE HE WAS LATER RELEASED. THE FREIGHT OPERATIONS SUPERVISOR WAS TRANSPORTED LATER AND WAS ALSO TREATED AND RELEASED. REMTECH ENGINEERING WAS NOTIFIED AND RESPONDED. REMTECH CONTAINED AND CLEANED THE SPILL. THE PUNCTURED DRUM WAS PLACED INTO AN OVERPACK DRUM AND ALL CLEAN UP WASTE WAS ALSO PLACED INTO A SALVAGE DRUM FOR LATER DISPOSAL INCIDENT COULD HAVE BEEN PREVENTED BY ENSURING THAT THERE WERE NO NAILS OR OTHER SHARP OBJECTS IN THE FLOOR.

WHO QUICKLY RESPONDED AND DETERMINED THERE WAS NO DANGER TO EMPLOYEES OR AIRCRAFT.  CONTAINER WAS REMOVED FROM AIRCRAFT.  RECIPIENT CAME TO COME PICK UP CONTAINER AT FACILITY.

column168: PACKAGE DISCOVERED LEAKING DURING SORT.  INSPECTION REVEALED LOOSE CAP ON PLASTIC BOTTLE.  PACKAGE PLACED IN STEEL SALVAGE DRUM. SHIPPER CONTACTED FOR PACKAGE DISPOSITION.
UNDECLARED LEAKING PACKAGE FOUND IN UPS FACILITY.

DURING THE SORT THIS PACKAGE WAS FOUND TO HAVE A SMALL DAMP SPOT. CLOSER INSPECTION REVEALED A SMALL LEAK FROM THE LOOSE TOPS OF THREE OF THE INNER CONTAINERS.  SHIPMENT WAS PLACED INSIDE A SALVAGE DRUM AND HELD PENDING DISPOSITION INSTRUCTIONS FROM THE CUSTOMER.

4 LITRE GLASS BOTTLE LEAKED INSIDE FIBREBOARD BOX.  CAUSE IS UNKNOWN.  REPORTED AS SMALL LEAK UNTIL PACKAGE OPENED.  UPON LOOKING INSIDE BOX FOUND THE ENTIRE CONTENTS EMPTY.  IT APPEARS THAT BOTTLE IS CRACKED.  PACKAGE DRUMMED AND AWAITING DISPOSITION FROM SHIPPER.
DRUM WAS DROPPED CAUSING A FAILURE AROUND THE LID.  PACKAGE WAS OVERPACKED IN A 1A2 SALVAGE DRUM AND DELIVERED.

column168: THE BOX WAS DROPPED ON THE CEMENT FLOOR AND THE BOX RIPPED OPEN. THIS ALLOWED THE REMAINING JET FUEL IN THE PART TO ESCAPE.  THE SHIPMENT WAS PLACED IN A SALVAGE DRUM AND FORWARDED TO THE RECIPIENT.

AS THE DRUM WAS SORTED A SMALL AMOUNT OF MATERIAL ESCAPED FROM THE LOOSE CAP.  BAKING SODA WAS APPLIED TO THE SPILL TO NEUTRALIZE IT. THE DRUM WAS PLACED INTO A SALVAGE DRUM AND RETURNED TO THE SHIPPER.

column42: GASOLINE INCLUDES GASOLINE MIXED WITH ETHYL ALCOHOL, WITH NOT MORE THAN 10% ALCOHOL
column168: THE RUBBER PIECES HAD A STRONG GASOLINE ODOR. THE PKG WAS PLACED IN A STEEL SALVAGE DRUM & HELD FOR THE FAA. I NOTIFIED SA ANDREW JOHNSON. THERE WERE NO MARKINGS, LABELING SHIPPING PAPERS OR OTHER INDICATORS TO LEAD US TO BELIEVE THE CONTENTS WERE REGULATED.

THE BOX WAS BEING SORTED WHEN IT BEGAN GIVING OFF A VERY DISAGREEABLE ODOR. THE BOX WAS REMOVED FROM THE SORT & PLACED IN A SALVAGE DRUM. THE SHIPPER WAS CONTACTED WHO INDICATED THE CYLIDER SHOULD HAVE BEEN SENT AS A COMPRESSED GAS. THE CONTENTS CONTAIN BUTANE, ISOBUTANE, & PROPANE. THERE WERE NO MARKINGS, LABELING OR SHIPPING PAPERS TO LEAD US TO BELIEVE THE CONTENTS WERE REGULATED. THE FAA WAS NOTIFIED, I SPOKE TO ROOY MORALES IN THE LAX CASFO.

THE PACKAGE WAS FOUND TO BE LEAKING. THE SPILLED MATERIAL & BOX WERE PLACED IN A SALVAGE DRUM. MATERIAL SAFETY DATA SHEET WAS FAXED TO US, THE FLASHPOINT WAS 141 DEGREES F. THE FAA WAS NOTIFIED. I SPOKE TO SA DON STEIGER. THERE WERE NO MARKINGS, LABELING, SHIPPING PAPERS, OR OTHER INDICATORS TO LEAD US TO BELIEVE THE CONTENTS WERE REGULATED.

column42: CARBON DIOXIDE, SOLID OR DRY ICE
column168: THE SHIPPER (RITA) SAID SHE PACKED A CHUNK OF DRY ICE INTO A PLASTIC BAG ALONG WITH A SPECIMEN INTO A MANILA ENVELOPE AND FURTHER OVERPACKED IT IN FEDEX BOX. NEITHER THE BOX NOR THE BAG VENTED AS THE DRY ICE VAPOR BUILT UP. THE ENSUING EXPLOSION BLEW THE ENDS OF THE BOX OUT. THE FAA WAS NOTIFIED. I SPOKE TO DIANA IN THE WESTERN REGION COMM CENTER & LATER DISCUSSED THE MATTER WITH TOM KENNY, JR. WE TOOK PICTURES THE KNIGHT OF THE INCIDENT. THE DISPOSABLE CAMERA WAS TURNED OVER TO THE FAA. THERE WERE NO MARKINGS, LABELING, OR SHIPPING PAPERS TO LEAD US TO BELIEVE THE CONTENTS WERE REGULATED.

column42: PETROLEUM DISTILLATES, N.O.S. OR PETROLEUM PRODUCTS, N.O.S.
column168: THIS PACKAGE HAD LEAKED IN A FEDEX CONTAINER (ULD#AMJ42469) WHEN IT ARRIVED IN ANCHORAGE FROM INDONESIA. THE MSDS WAS REQUESTED FROM THE SHIPPER BUT HAS NOT BEEN GIVEN TO FEDEX AT THIS POINT. SINCE THIS WAS AN ONLY SUBSTANCE AND COULD BE A POSSIBLE UNDECLARED DANGEROUS GOODS, THIS IS BEING HELD FOR FAA INVESTIGATION. THERE ARE NO DANGEROUS GOODS MARKINGS OR LABELINGS ON THE OUTER BOX AND THERE WAS NO HAZARDOUS MATERIAL PAPERWORK OFFERED TO FEDERAL  EXPRESS. ALSO, "NO" WAS CHECKED ON THE AIRWAYBILL FOR DANGEROUS GOODS IN THE SHIPMENT. THIS MATERIAL WAS DESCRIBED AS "SLAT" ON THE AIRWAYBILL AND THE COMMERCIAL INVOICE.
column172: Plastic container, no capacity or description given

column168: THIS BOX OF AIRCRAFT PARTS PUT OFF AN ODOR FROM THE SPILL OF FUEL IN THE FUEL PUMP PIECE. THIS WAS INSPECTED AND CLEANED UP BY THE SPILL CLEAN UP SPECIALIST. AN MSDS WAS FOUND AND THIS WAS GIVEN A FLASHPOINT OF GREATER THAN 100 DEGREES FARENHEIT. THE FAA WAS NOTIFIED, SINCE THIS MAY BE CONSIDERED A HIDDEN DANGEROUS GOODS SHIPMENT. THERE WERE NO MARKINGS OR LABELINGS FOR DANGEROUS GOODS ON THE BOX AND NO DANGEROUS GOODS PAPERWORK WAS OFFERED TO FEDEX. THIS IS CURRENTLY BEING HELD FOR AN FAA INVESTIGATION

THIS IS A FUEL INJECTION PUMP THAT CONTAINED DIESEL FUEL. IT APPEARS THAT IT WAS NOT SECURED, DRAINED, AND/OR DRIED OUT AND THEREFORE THIS PART LEAKED AND CAUSED AN ODOR AND STAINS ON THE OUTER BOX. THERE WAS NO MSDS WITH THE SHIPMENT AND THERE WERE NO MARKINGS OR LABELINGS ON THE PACKAGE. THE FEDEX FACILITY IN ANCHORAGE IS STILL WAITING ON AN MSDS FROM THE SHIPPER. BECAUSE SOME DIESEL FUEL IS CONSIDERED FLAMMABLE, THIS SHIPMENT WAS HELD FOR AN FAA INVESTIGATION. THERE WAS NO DANGEROUS GOODS PAPERWORK OFFERED TO FEDEX.

DRUMS WERE TURNED ON SIDE AND PATCHED, AND PUT IN RECOVERY DRUMS TO BE RETURNED TO SHIPPER. UPON INSPECTION OF DRUMS IT HAS BEEN DETERMINED THAT DRUMS WERE PUNCTURED WITH DRUM HANDLING TRUCK.
WHILE WALKING AROUND THE REAR OF TRAILER. THE DRIVER NOTICED A DRIP AT DISCHARGE LINE. THE DRIVER PUT A BUCKET UNDER LEAK AND CALLED DISPATCH. VALVES WILL BE CHECKED PRIOR TO LOADING.
DOCKMAN SAW SOME SMOKE COMING FROM A DRUM AND SUPERVISOR WAS NOTIFIED. A DRUM HAD SWOLLEN AT THE TOP, A CLEAN UP COMPANY WAS CALLED TO VENT THE DRUM AND THE DRUM WAS SENT ONTO DESTINATION.

column168: DURING HANDLING AT CARRIERS FACILITY THE PRODUCT DISCHARGE VALVE OF THE PACKAGE WAS DAMAGED RESULTING IN A LEAK. THE PACKAGE WAS SECURED TO PREVENT FURTHER LOSS OF PRODUCT. THE SPILLED MATERIAL WAS PICKED UP WITH ABSORBENTS PUT INTO DRUMS AND SET ASIDE FOR PICK UP BY A DISPOSAL CONTRACTOR. THE TRAILER WAS MOVED AWAY FROM THE DOCK TO BE AIRED OUT. THE SHIPPER PROVIDED A SALVAGE DRUM DESIGNED FOR THAT PARTICULAR PACKAGE. THE PACKAGE WAS OVRPACKED AND FORWARDED TO THE CONSIGNEE.

A SHIPMENT OF 15 CARTONS WAS SHRINK WRAPPED TO A PALLET. TWO CARTONS WERE CRUSHED DUE TO THE SHRINK WRAP BEING DRAWN TOO TIGHTLY. ONE PLASTIC JUG IN ONE OF THE CARTONS WAS BROKEN OPEN AS A RESULT, SPILLING ITS ENTIRE CONTENTS. CONSIGNEE PROVIDED MATERIALS AND ASSISTANCE TO CLEAN THE TRAILER.

THE DOCK EMPLOYEE WHO HAD PLACED THE FREIGHT ON THE DOCK FLOOR HAD TRIPLE STACKED FREIGHT. EMPLOYEE HAD PLACED A PALLET OF LIQUID FILLED THE PAILS ATOP A SKID OF CARDBOARD CARTONS CONTAINING POWDERED MATERIAL. OVER TIME THE CARDBOARD CARTONS COLLAPSED UNDER THE WEIGHT OF THE LIQUID FILLED PAILS THEREBY CAUSING THE PALLETS OF PAILS TO TOPPLE ON TO THE DOCK FLOOR. WHEN THE PAILS FELL, ONE PAIL ON THE PALLET RUPTURED AND RELEASED ITS ENTIRE CONTENTS.

DAMAGED DRUM WAS DISCOVERED ON DOCK FLOOR. DRUM HAD BEEN COMPRESSED IN AS IF IT HAD BEEN STRUCK BY FORKLIFT COUNTERWEIGHT. COMPRESSION OF DRUM CAUSED A CRIMP TO FROM ON THE LOWER CHIME OF THE DRUM. A CRACK HAD FORMED AT THE POINT WHERE DRUM HAD CRIMPED.

DOCK EMPLOYEE WAS UNLOADING FREIGHT FROM TRAILER. WHEN EMPLOYEE CROSSED OVER DOCK PLATE INTO TRAILER, HIS FORKLIFT JUMPED AS HE  WAS MOVING FORWARD. HIS FORKLIFT THEN STRUCK A PAIL WHICH WAS LOADED ON A PALLET AT THE TRAILER.

CONTENTS OF THE PORTA-FEED SPILLED INSIDE THE TRAILER AND ONTO THE PARKING LOT OF THE FACILITY. RM CAT AND ENVIRONMENTAL SERVICE WAS CALLED TO CLEAN UP THE SPILL. THE TRAILER WAS UNLOADED, DECONTAMINATED AND RELOADED WITH THE PRODUCT. IT WAS FOUND THAT THE PORTA-FEED WAS LEAKING FROM THE TOP BUNG ON THE MANWAY COVER. FURTHER INVESTIGATION FOUND THE TEFLON GASKET AND GROOVED. THE GASKET WAS TURNED OVER THE TRAILER FLOOR BETWEEN THE PORTA-FEED AND THE INSIDE NOSE OF THE TRAILER. THIS PALLET WOULD NOT PREVENT THE LOAD FROM SHIFTING EVEN IN A HARD BRAKING SITUATION. SHIPPER IS LOOKING AT A BETTER BRACING SYSTEM FOR BULK HEAD TO PREVENT LOADS FROM SHIFTING.

column168: 4 DAMS LOADED ON SKID NO CARDBOARD ON SKID PALLET BROKE NAIL PROTRUDING. PUNCTURED BOTTOM OF DRUM. CAUSING SPILL OF APPROX 40 GALLONS.
WHEN DRIVER LOADED THE DRUM INTO A TRAILER, THE BOTTOM OF THE DRUM CAUGHT ON A RIVIT HEAD, PUNCTURING THE DRUM.

1 55 GALLON STEEL DRUM WAS SEERING A SMALL AMOUNT OF LIQUID APPROX 24 INCHES FROM TOP OF DRUM.  DRUM WAS PUT ON IT SIDE THEN PLACED IN RECOVERY DRUM AND RETURNED TO SHIPPER SMALL AMOUNT OF RELEASED PRODUCT EVAPORATED HOLE REPAIRED WITH PLUG A DYRE.

column58: Auxiliary Valve; Bottom Outlet Valve; Piping or Fittings
column168: DRIVER WAS IN ROUTE ON NORTHBOUND INTERSTATE 85 TO TANNER CHEMICAL WHEN HE NOTICED A WHITE CLOUD OF LIQUID NITROGEN COMING FROM UNDERNEATH THE TRAILER.  HE THEN PULLED OFF INTERSTATE 85 AT EXIT 59 TO EXAMINE THE BOTTOM OF THE TRAILER.  HE NOTICED THAT THE BOTTOM FILL VALVE HAD VIBRATED OPEN AND FROZE IN THIS POSITION, THE DRIVER WAS UNABLE TO CLOSE THE VALVE. THE GEORGIA SOUTH POLICE ARRIVED AND IT WAS DETERMINED THAT THE RAMP SHOULD BE CLOSED.  AIR PRODUCTS DISPATCHED A MECHANIC TO THE SCENE AND WAS ABLE TO FIX THE VALVE AND GET IT CLOSED.  THE DRIVER WAS THEN ABLE TO CONTINUE AND COMPLETE HIS DELIVERIES WITH NO FURTHER INCIDENT.

column42: ETHYLENE OXIDE OR ETHYLENE OXIDE WITH NITROGEN UP TO A TOTAL PRESSURE OF 1MPA (10 BAR) AT 50 DEGREES C
column168: DERAILMENT, NO RELEASE, EVACUATION ONLY UTLX 89898, SEPTEMBER 7, 1999, DETROIT DIVISION , AT APPROXIMATELY 0750 HOURS, TUESDAY, SEPTEMBER 7, 1999 AT MILE POST 7.8 RIVER ROUGE YARD RIVER ROUGE MI CONRAIL YARD LOCAL TRAIN YPPR23 WORKING IN THE NORTH END OF RIVER ROUGE YARD HAD CARS RUN OUT SOUTH END OF #3 TRACK INTO MGL10 TRAIN. YPPRR23 YARD LOCAL TRAIN DERAILED GTW 127053, AN EMPTY RACK CAR AND UTLX 89898 CONTAINING ETHYLENE OXIDE DERAILED AND LANDED ON ITS SIDE. APPROPRIATE NOTIFICATION MADE. UTLX 89898 DID NOT RELEASE ANY PRODUCT. FOR PRECAUTIONARY MEASURES, APPROXIMATELY 600 PEOPLE WERE EVACUATED BY ORDER OF LOCAL EMERGENCY RESPONSE PERSONNEL. AT APPROXIMATELY 0715 HOURS, TUESDAY, SEPTEMBER 14, 1999, AT THE TRENTON AVENUE BRANCH IN PHILADELPHIA, PA NS TRAIN CAAL4 DERAILED THE FOLLOWING THREE HAZARDOUS MATERIAL CARS:  UTLX 47516 DERAILED A-END ONLY.  NO PRODUCT LOSS.  AT APPROXIMATELY 0145 HOURS, SEPTEMBER 15, 1999, THE TANK CAR WAS RERAILED AND ROLLER BEARING INSPECTION WILL BE CONDUCTED.  UTLX 660290 DERAILED AND FELL OFF THE TRENTON RAIL BRIDGE AND LANDED ON THE STREET BELOW, IN AN APPROXIMATE 175 DEGREES FROM THE UPRIGHT POSITION. THE TANK CAR LOST APPROXIMATELY 7500 GALLONS OF PRODUCT.  APPROXIMATELY 25 PEOPLE WERE EVACUATED FROM THE IMMEDIATE AREA.  CONRAIL'S MANAGER OF HAZARDOUS MATERIALS ARRIVED AT THE SITE.  REACT AND CLEAN HARBOR'S, ENVIRONMENTAL REMEDIATION CONTRACTORS ARRIVED AT THE SITE.  THE IMPACT FROM HITTING THE STREET CAUSED THE MANWAY NOZZLE TO BE SLIGHTLY CRUSHED AT THE AL AREA OF THE NOZZLE.  APPROXIMATELY THREE MANWAY COVER SECUREMENT BOLTS BROKE AWAY FROM THE MANWAY ALLOWING PRODUCT TO BE RELEASED.  THE TANK CAR WAS TRANSFERRED, UPRIGHTED AND LOADED ONTO A FLATBED TRUCK AND DELIVERED BACK TO THE SHIPPER.  SUN COMPANY, FRANKFORD PLANT IN PHILADELPHIA.  THE TANK CAR JACKET AND INSULATION WERE REMOVED, DECONTAMINATED AND PROPERLY DISPOSED.  THE TANK WAS CLEANED, PURGED AND SCRAPPED AT THE SUN COMPANY SITE BY REACT.  PTLX 120134 DERAILED AND ROLLED TO ITS LEFT SIDE APPROXIMATELY 45 DEGREES.  CONRAIL'S MANAGER OF HAZARDOUS MATERIALS EXAMINED THE TANK CAR AND DETERMINED THAT BOTH ENDS DETRUCKED.  THE BOTTOM OUTLET AUXILLARY VALVE SHEARED OFF AS DESIGNED ALTHOUGH INTERIOR VALVE REMAINED INTACT, NO LEAKAGE.  NEGLIGIBLE RELEASE FROM VACUUM RELIEF VALVE. BOTTOM OUTLET MOUNTING FLANGE AND CLOSURES REPLACED BY SHIPPER PRIOR TO MOVEMENT.  TANK CAR WILL BE RETURNED TO SUN COMPANY FOR UNLOADING, CLEANING, PURGING AND SCRAPPING.

column42: BATTERIES, WET, FILLED WITH ACID, ELECTRIC STORAGE
column62: Improper Preparation for Transportation; Inadequate Blocking and Bracing
column168: GENERAL PARTS/CARQUEST IS A DISTRIBUTOR OF AUTO PARTS AND ACCESSORIES. THE SETTING FOR THE INCIDENT WAS THE LOADING DOCK AREA OF AN AUTO PARTS STORE.  THE DRIVER INVOLVED HAD ONE STOP REMAINING ON HIS NIGHTLY DELIVERY RUN.  HE WAS IN THE CARGO BOX MOVING DELIVERIES FOR THE FINAL STOP TO THE REAR OF THE TRUCK.  THE DRIVER PLACED A WET BATTERY IN THE LIFTGATE AREA AND RETURNED TO MOVE ADDITIONAL ITEMS TO THE REAR.  DURING THE PROCESS, THE DRIVER SAT A FIVE GALLON CAN OF LACQUER THINNER ON TOP OF THE WET BATTERY. THE BATTERY ARCED WHEN THE CAN MADE CONTACT WITH THE POSTS AND A EXPLOSION/FLASH FIRE OCCURRED.  THE DRIVER WAS INJURED, BUT WAS ABLE TO MOVE THE TRUCK AWAY FROM THE LOADING DOCK AND CALL 911.  LOCAL LAW ENFORCEMENT, FIRE AND MEDICAL PERSONNEL RESPONDED. THE CARGO BOX BURNED. THE DRIVER WAS TREATED IN THE HOSPITAL BURN UNIT AND HIS RECOVERY PROGNOSIS IS GOOD.  THERE WAS NO DANGER OR THREAT TO ANYONE OTHER THAN THE DRIVER INVOLVED.  NO CONTAMINATION OF THE ENVIRONMENT OR HAZMAT CLEANUP WAS REQUIRED.  PREVENTION STEPS TAKEN INCLUDE RECURRENT TRAINING FOR ALL PERSONNEL INVOLVED IN THE TRANSPORTATION OF HAZMAT AT OUR GREAT BEND, KS LOCATION WITH SPECIAL EMPHASIS PLACED ON THE PACKING, LOADING AND UNLOADING OF BATTERIES.  THE DRIVER INVOLVED HAD RECEIVED HIS MOST RECENT HM-126F TRAINING PRIOR TO THE INCIDENT ON 3/05/99.

column168: DRIVER OF UNIT #1 HAD PICKED UP TRAILER #1931 AND DROVE LESS THAN 1 MILE TO THE LOADING RACK AT THE CONOCO FACILITY IN COMMERCE CITY, CO.  HE LOADED AVIATION FUEL, JP8, AND PROCEEDED TO PETERSON AFB IN COLORADO SPRINGS, CO.  WHILE TRAVELING SOUTH ON I-25, SOUTH OF THE DOWNTOWN AREA OF DENVER, THE TRAILER CAME OFF THE FIFTH WHEEL OF THE TRACTOR.  THE TRAILER FELL DOWN ONTO ITS NOSE AND TRAVELED ALONG THE PAVEMENT FOR APPROXIMATELY 100 YARDS BEFORE STOPPING.  THE LOADING FACILITY AT CONOCO IN COMMERCE CITY IS BOTTOM LOADING.  WHEN THE TRAILER BECAME DISLOGED FROM THE TRACTOR IT FELL ONTO ITS NOSE THEN ONTO THE GROUND.  WHEN THE TRAILER CONTACTED THE GROUND, THE FRONT DISCHARGE TUBE ON #1 COMPARTMENT WAS TORN OFF BY THE ROADWAY.  SINCE THE TRAILER WAS BOTTOM LOADED, THE PRODUCT CONTAINED IN THE DISCHARGE TUBE ESCAPED AND SPILLED.  THE SPILLAGE IS ESTIMATED AT 10 GALLONS.  THE FIRE VALVE IN #1 COMPARTMENT, ASSOCIATED WITH THE DISLODGED DISCHARGE TUBE HELD TIGHT AND NO FURTHER PRODUCT WAS LOST FROM THE COMPARTMENT.  THE TUBE AND FIRE VALVE PERFORMED AS DESIGNED.  THE TUBE BROKE AWAY, AND THE FIRE VALVE HELD SECURE.  THE ROADWAY IN THE AREA OF THE INCIDENT IS VERY WAVY OR WASHBOARD.  THIS CAUSES THE TRACTOR/TRAILER COMBINATION TO "BUCK" UP AND DOWN AND CONSEQUENTLY THE TRAILER BECAME DISLODGED. THROUGHT INVESTIGATION, IT WAS FOUND THAT THE DRIVER HAD NOT PROPERLY ENGAGED THE LOCKING JAWS ON THE FIFTH WHEEL CAUSING THE TRAILER TO DISCONNECT WHEN THE UNIT BEGAN TO "BUCK" FROM THE WASHBOARD ROAD SURFACE

WHILE UNLOADING TRAILER A BAG WAS FOUND TORN AND LEAKING. A CERTIFIED HAZARDOUS MATERIALS RESPONSE TEAM WAS CALLED TO THE SCENE TO RECOUPER BAG AND MINOR SPILLAGE. THE ENTIRE PALLET WAS RETURNED TO SHIPPER FOR CLAIMS CREDIT.

WHILE UNLOADING TRAILER FORKLIFT CREASED SIDE OF DRUM. THE TRAILER WAS EVACUATED AND A CERTIFIED HAZARDOUS MATERIALS TEAM WAS CALLED TO THE SCENE. THE TEAM RECOUPED AND OVERPACKED THE DAMAGED DRUM WHICH WAS RETURNED TO SHIPPER FOR CLAIMS CREDIT.

WHILE UNLOADING CHECKER FOUND A CARTON CRUSHED AND LEAKING. THE BOX WAS RECOUPED AND OVERPACKED INTO A DOT APPROVED SALVAGE DRUM WHICH WAS HELD FOR DISPOSITION. ALL SPILLAGE HARDENED AND WAS DISPOSED OF PROPERLY.

column168: PASCHALL TRUCK LINES WAS TRANSPORTING 10 TANKS FROM INSTITUTE, WV. TO SUGARLAND, TEXAS. IN LUFKIN, TEXAS A CAR PULLED ACROSS IN FRONT OF PTL, TO AVOID NITTING THE CAR PTL HIT HIS BRAKES CAUSING THE LOAD TO SHIFT FORWARD. PTL GOT OUT TO INSPECT HIS LOAD AND NOTICED HE HAD PRODUCT LEAKING FROM THE NOSE OF THE TRAILER. PTL NOTIFIED THE SHERIFF'S DEPT. WHO IN TURN NOTIFIED PTL. PTL CALLED EMI AND A SUBCONTRACTOR FROM LONGVIEW, TX. WAS SENT TO THE SCENE. AFTER INSPECTING THE TRAILER IT WAS DISCOVERED THAT 2 TANKS WHERE LEAKING IN THE NOSE OF THE TRAILER. A TANKER WAS BROUGHT IN AND THE REMAINDER OF PRODUCT IN THE 2 DAMAGED TOTES WHERE PUMPED OUT INTO THE TANKER. IT WAS 860 GALLONS. THEN PTL WAS TAKEN TO A PAPER MILL IN LUFKIN, TX. THAT HAD A DOCK AREA SO THE WHOLE LOAD COULD BE OFF LOADED, DECONTAMINATED AND RELOADED. AFTER BEING RELOADED DRIVER CONTINUED TO CONSIGNEE. THE TWO DAMAGED TANKS AND 2 TANKS THAT WHERE DENTED REMAINED ON THE TRAILER. SO THE CONSIGNEE ACCEPTED 6 TANKS.THEN THE CONSIGNEE LOADED 2 NEW EMPTY TANKS SO PTL COULD RETURN TO LUFKIN, TX. AND HAVE THE 860 GALLONS IN THE TANKER PUMPED INTO THE TANKS FOR RETURN TO THE SHIPPER IN INSTITUTE, WV. THIS WAS COMPLETED AND PTL RETURNED TO INSTITUTE, WV. AND ARRIVED WITH NO FURTHER PROBLEMS.

A SAFETY KLEEN DRIVER AT HEATH,OH FACILITY NOTICED AN ODOR COMING FROM THE BACK OF HIS TRAILER, UPON INVESTIGATION HE FOUND LIQUID ON THE FLOOR OF THE TRAILER. THE TRAILER WAS HAULING 14 DRUMS OF WASTE POTASSIUM HYDROXIDE SOLUTION. APPROXIMATELY 1 PINT OF LIQUID HAD LEAKED FROM THE BOTTOM SEAL OF A DRUM. THE SPILL WAS CONTAINED IN THE TRAILER. THE DRUMS WERE IN ROUTE TO THE SAFETY-KLEEN FACILITY IN GREENBRIER, TN. AN EMERGENCY RESPONSE TEAM WAS DISPATCHED FROM THE SAFETY-KLEEN FACILITY IN HEBRON,OH. THE EMERGENCY RESPONSE TEAM OVERPACKED THE LEAKING DRUM AND CLEANED UP THE SPILL WITH ABSORBENT PADS. ONLY 4 POUNDS OF ADDITIONAL WASTE WAS PRODUCED FROM THE SPILL. THIS MATERIAL ALONG WITH THE ORIGINAL DRUM WAS SENT TO THE SAFETY-KLEEN FACILITY 2815 OLD GREENBRIER,TN. THE SAFETY-KLEEN EMPLOYEE INVOLVED IN THE SPILL REVIEWED PROCEDURES FOR INSPECTING DRUMS BEFORE TRANSPORTING WITH HIS SUPERVISOR.

AT THIS FACILITY DRUMMED WASTE MATERIAL IS TRANSFERRED VIA PUMP INTO CARGO TANKS FOR SHIPMENT TO THE FINAL TSDF. DURING THIS OPERATION IT WAS DISCOVERED THAT THE HOSE GOING FROM THE PUMP TO THE CARGO TANK HAD NOT BEEN PROPERLY FITTED INTO THE CARGO TANK. THEREFORE THE MATERIAL BEING PUMPED OUT OF THE DRUMS WAS NOT GOING INTO THE CARGO TANK BUT BEING SPILLED INTO THE SECONDARY CONTAINMENT SYSTEM. TRANSFERRING OF MATERIAL WAS STOPPED IMMEDIATELY AFTER DISCOVERY OF THE MIS-FITTED HOSE. THE WASTE MATERIAL THAT WAS RELEASED INTO SECONDARY CONTAINMENT WAS PUMPED BACK INTO THE CARGO TANK AND WILL BE DISPOSED OF AT THE LISTED DESIGNATED FACILITY IN DOLTON,IL. THE SECONDARY CONTAINMENT AREA WAS THEN WIPED DOWN WITH ABSORBENT PADS. THE SPILL GENERATED APPROXIMATELY 30 GALLONS OF ADDITIONAL WASTE IN THE FORM OF ABSORBENT PADS THAT WILL BE TRANSPORTED TO SAFETY-KLEEN TSDF LOCATED AT 581 MILLIKEN DRIVE SE, HEBRON FOR RECYCLING. THE SAFETY-KLEEN EMPLOYEE RESPONSIBLE FOR THIS TRANSFER REVIEWED  THE SAFETY-KLEEN STANDARD OPERATING PROCEDURES FOR THIS OPERATION WITH HIS SUPERVISOR IN ORDER TO PREVENT SUCH OCCURRENCES IN THE FUTURE.

A SALVAGE DRUM OF WASTE SODIUM HYDROXIDE SOLUTION FELL ONTO ITS SIDE WHILE BEING TRANSFERRED TO THE SAFETY-KLEEN FACILITY IN CASEYVILLE,IL. APPROXIMATELY 1/2 GALLON OF MATERIAL LEAKED ONTO THE FLOOR OF THE TRAILER FROM AROUND THE SEAL OF THE LID. THE SPILL WAS CONTAINED WITHIN THE TRAILER. THE EMPLOYEE STOOD THE SALVAGE DRUM UP AND CLEANED UP THE SPILL WITH ABSORBENT PADS WHICH WERE ADDED TO THE SALVAGE DRUM TO BE TRANSPORTED FOR DISPOSAL. THE SALVAGE DRUM WAS RESEALED AND LOADED ONTO THE TRUCK. THE SPILL GENERATED AN ADDITIONAL 4 POUNDS OF WASTE. THIS WILL BE DISPOSED OF ALONG WITH THE ORIGINAL DRUM AT THE SAFETY-KLEEN FACILITY AT 1722 COOPER CREEK ROAD,DENTON,TX. THE SAFETY-KLEEN EMPLOYEE RESPONSIBLE FOR THIS SPILL REVIEWED THE POLICIES REGARDING DRUM LOADING AND UNLOADING WITH HIS SUPERVISOR. THE EMPLOYEE WAS INSTRUCTED TO CHECK THE SEAL ON THE DRUMS BEFORE TRANSPORTING.

AT THIS FACILITY A DRUM WAS PICKED UP FROM A CLIENT AND WAS TO BE TRANSFERRED TO THE FINAL DESTINATION. DURING THE TRANSPORTATION THE DRIVER STOPPED AT THE SAFETY-KLEEN FACILITY TO UNLOAD OTHER DRUMS WHEN HE NOTICED A RUPTURED HAD OCCURRED ON THE DRUM. 35 GALLONS OF THE MATERIAL LEAKED INTO THE SECONDARY CONTAINMENT OF THE TRAILER. THE FACILITY EMPLOYEE NOTICED THE LEAKING CONTAINER. THE TRAILER WAS DRAINED OF ALL THE LIQUID AND THE ORIGINAL PLOY DRUM WAS OVERPACKED. ALL THE MATERIAL WAS PLACED INTO THE OVERPACKED AND SENT TO THE SAFETY-KLEEN FACILITY AT 1722 COOPER CREEK ROAD. DENTON, TX. THE SAFETY-KLEEN EMPLOYEE RESPONSIBLE FOR THIS SPILL REVIEWED THE POLICIES FOR INSPECTING DRUMS BEFORE TRANSPORTATION WITH HIS SUPERVISOR IN ORDER TO PREVENT FURTHER OCCURRENCES.

column168: DRIVER STARTED THE STANDARD AIR UNLOAD PROCESS USING PROPER PROCEDURE AND PER E.I DUPONT POLICY WENT TO PRESCRIBED PROTECTED AREA CLOSE BY TRUCK. SHORTLY AFTER UNLOADING COMMENCED A POLYPROPYLENE FITTING WHICH CONNECTS A HOSE TO THE CINSIGNEE TANK SPOUT APPARENTLY BROKE. THIS FITTING/HOSE WHICH IS SUPPLIED BY VENDOR IS LEFT IN PLACE AND USED BY SEVERAL DELIVERIES CARRIES. IT ATTACHES TO A SPOUT FIXED PARALLEL TO THE GROUND SEVERAL FEET IN THE AIR. THE FITTING/HOSE IS NOT EXTERNALLY SUPPORTED IN ANY WAY. ANY MOVEMENT OF THE HOSE DUE TO AIR PRESSURE OR THE FLOW OF PRODUCT IS ABSORBED BY THE FITTING WHICH WAS NEW AND HAS BEEN APPROPRIATELY PRESSURE TESTED IN FEBRUARY 99 AND CARRIED A BAND ATTESTING TO SAME. THE FITTING/HOSE IS NOT A PART OF THE ABOVE CARGO TANK TRAILER EQUIPMENT.THE DRIVER BECAME AWARE OF THE FITTING FAILURE WITH IN A SHORT TIME AFTER IT OCCURRED BECAUSE OF HIS OBSERVATION OF THE LIQUID SPILLING ON THE ASPHALT AND SHUT DOWN THE TRAILER IMMEDIATELY BY CLOSING THE LOWER AND UPPER VALVES ON THE TRAILER. THERE WERE NO FAILURE OF ANY KIND ASSOCIATED WITH THE TRUCK OR THE TRAILER OR THE EQUIPMENT ACCOMPANY THEM. THE CHEMICAL WHICH WAS UNLOADED (SODIUM HYPOCHLORITE) IS USED FOR TREATMENT OF AN OPEN UNLINED CHEMICAL TREATMENT POND LOCATED 20 FEET FROM THE UNLOADING TRUCK. THE ENTIRE SPILL RAN ACROSS DEPRESSION IN THE ASPHALT UNLOAD AREA THRU SEVERAL FEET OF LIMESTONE GRAVEL AND DIRECTLY INTO THE CHEMICAL TREATMENT POND 20 FEET FROM THE TRUCK. THE PRODUCT LOSS FIGURE ON THE FRONT OF IS FORM ASSUMES THAT THE SPILL WAS LOST WHICH PREVENTION OF FUTURE INCIDENTS.

AFTER RETURNING TO THE FACILITY A SAFETY KLEEN EMPLOYEE OPENED THE BACK DOORS TO UNLOAD THE TRUCK AND NOTICED THAT A 16 GALLON METAL DRUM HAD TIPPED WHILE IN TRANSIT. APPROXIMATELY 2 GALLONS OF LIQUID ONTO THE FLOOR OF THE TRUCK. THE DRUM WAS RIGHTED AND ABSORBENT WAS PLACED ON THE SPILL. THE SPILL CLEAN UP MATERIAL WAS CONTANERIZED FOR DISPOSAL. THE RELEASE PRODUCED APPROXIMATELY 15 POUNDS OF ADDITIONAL WASTE. THIS WASTE WAS SENT ALONG WITH THE ORIGINAL DRUM TO THE SAFETY-KLEEN FACILITY AT 633 EAST 138TH STREET, DOLTON,ILLINOIS FOR DISPOSAL. THE EMPLOYEES REVIEWED THE SAFETY-KLEEN STANDARD OPERATING PROCEDURES FOR MATERIAL LOADING AND DRUM HANDLING WITH HIS SUPERVISOR. THE EMPLOYEES WERE COUNSELED ON PROPER LOADING PROCEDURES.

AS AN EMPLOYEE WAS UNLOADING A PALLET OF DRUMS FROM BACK OF TRAILER, THE PALLET BROKE RESULTING IN A 55 GALLON DRUM BEING RUPTURED BY A FORKLIFT. THE LEAKING DRUM WAS IMMEDIATELY CONTAINED. ONE GALLON OF WASTE MATERIAL WAS RELEASED INTO THE BACK OF THE TRUCK. THIS SPILL GENERATED 15 POUNDS OF ADDITIONAL WASTE THAT WAS TRANSPORTED, ALONG WITH THE OVER PACKED DRUM TO THE SAFETY-KLEEN FACILITY AT 3700 LAGRANGE ROAD IN SMITHVILLE FOR DISPOSAL. THE DRIVER WAS COUNSELED IN A REVIEW OF APPROVED OPERATING PROCEDURES FOR SECURING LOADS AND TRANSPORTING MATERIALS WITH A FORKLIFT.

SWS INSPECTED CAR; THE MANWAY COVER GASKET LOOKED NEW BUT IT APPEARED TO BE TO THIN TO FORM A SEAL.  GASKET HAD LOTS OF SILICON SEALANT APPLIED. SWS REPLACED THIS MANWAY GASKET WITH A BUTYL NITRILE GASKET THEY OBTAINED FROM LOCAL VENDOR.  CAR WAS SECURED AND RELEASED.  CAR BELONGS TO ASHLAND CHEM.

WHILE SERVICING A CLIENT, THE SAFETY-KLEEN EMPLOYEE KNOCKED A 16 GALLON STEEL DRUM OFF THE LIFT GATE OF THE TRUCK.  APPROXIMATELY 7 GALLONS OF LIQUID SPILLED ONTO THE CONCRETE.  THE DRUM WAS RIGHTED AND ABSORBENT PADS AND SORBENT WERE PLACED ON THE SPILL.  THE SPILL CLEANUP MATERIAL WAS PLACED INTO A DRUM FOR DISPOSAL.  THE RELEASE PRODUCED APPROXIMATELY 25 POUNDS OF ADDITIONAL WASTE.  THIS WASTE WAS SENT ALONG WITH ORIGINAL DRUM AND WILL BE SENT TO THE SAFETY-KLEEN FACILITY AT 1311 SOUTH ANNA IN WICHITA, KANSAS AND TREATED AS BRANCH WASTE.  THE EMPLOYEE REVIEWED THE SAFETY-KLEEN STANDARD OPERATING PROCEDURES FOR MATERIAL LOADING AND DRUM HANDLING WITH HIS SUPERVISOR.  THE EMPLOYEE WERE COUNSELED ON PROPER LOADING PROCEDURES.

column62: Fire, Temperature, or Heat; Vehicular Crash or Accident Damage
column168: CAME AROUND BEND AND VAN HAD LOST CONTROL AHEAD OF OUR DRIVER AND HIT HIM HEAD ON CAUSING A CHAIN REACTION. ON SEPTEMBER 6, 1999, A PETROLEUM TRANSPORTER OPERATED BY INLAND CORP. WAS INVOLVED IN AN ACCIDENT ON US HIGHWAY 160 NEAR MILE MARKER 288, NEAR LA VETA, COLORADO.  AS A RESULT OF THE ACCIDENT, APPROXIMATELY 6,200 GALLONS OF MTBE WERE SPILLED AT TWO LOCATIONS. THE SPILL SITES ARE LOCATED IN THE ROADSIDE DITCH ON THE SOUTH SIDE OF THE HIGHWAY AND ON PRIVATE PROPERTY ADJACENT TO THE HIGHWAY.  AN UNKNOWN VOLUME OF DIESEL FUEL WAS SPILLED FROM THE TRUCK'S FUEL TANKS AT ANOTHER LOCATION IN THE ROADSIDE DITCH.  ALTHOUGH SOME OF THE MTBE SPILLED ON PRIVATE PROPERTY AND SOME OF THE DIESEL FUEL BURNED IN THE  ENSUING FIRE, MTBE AND DIESEL FUEL SOAKED INTO THE SOIL.  LMH ENVIRONMENTAL, INC., WAS AUTHORIZED BY GREAT WEST CASUALTY COMPANY, THE INSURER FOR INLAND CORP., TO COMPLETE THE ENVIRONMENTAL CLEANUP OF THE SITE.

column168: NS 271077 WAS NOTED LEAKING PRODUCT FROM A BOTTOM HOPPER DOOR BY CARRIER PERSONNEL.  CAR ISOLATED AND SHIPPER NOTIFIED. column62: Rollover Accident; Vehicular Crash or Accident Damage; Rollover Accident; Vehicular Crash or Accident Damage
column168: ON SEPTEMBER 13,1999 AT 3:00PM, BFI WASTE SYSTEM OF NORTH AMERICA WAS INVOLVED IN A HAZARDOUS MATERIAL INCIDENT. A TRUCK (#80121) WAS GOING SOUTHBOUND ON PA STATE ROAD 0018 IN ERIE, COUNTY PA 2/10 OF A MILE SOUTH OF MESSENGER ROAD. THE TRUCK WAS ON REGULAR ROUTE TO COLLECT REGULATED MEDICAL WASTE. THE VEHICLE WAS TRANSPORTING REGULATED MEDICAL WASTE IN THE FOLLOWING NON-BULK CONTAINER: WHITE MOP RINGER-MWS30 REUSABLE PLASTIC CONTAINER 4H2/Y35.6/S/99/USA/+AA2030 FIBERBOARD BOX OF 45 CUBIC FEET. DURING TRANSPORTATION AN ANIMAL RAN ACROSS THE ROAD. IN AN ATTEMPT TO AVOID THE ANIMAL, THE BFI DRIVER TURNED TO THE LEFT THEN TO THE RIGHT GOING OFF THE RIGHT SIDE OF THE ROAD. THE DRIVER THEN TURNED BACK TO THE LEFT, BRINGING THE TRUCK BACK ON THE ROAD. THE TRUCK THEN TURNED OVER ON ITS RIGHT SIDE. THE TRUCK TURNING OVER ON IT'S SIDE CAUSED A NUMBER OF THE MWS30 REUSABLE PLASTIC CONTAINERS TO INVERT WITHIN THE CONFINES OF THE TRUCK. APPROXIMATELY TWO GALLONS OF SOME LIQUID LEAKED FROM TWO OF THE INVERTED CONTAINERS. THE TYPE AND SOURCE OF THE LIQUID IS UNKNOWN. ALTHOUGH MOST OF THE LIQUID WAS CONTAINED WITHIN THE VEHICLE SOME OF IT LEAKED OUT OF A HOLE IN THE RIGHT FRONT TOP CORNER OF THE TRUCK. THE HOLE WAS CAUSED BY THE TRUCK TURNING OVER ON ITS SIDE. FOLLOWING THE INCIDENT THE BFI DRIVER REPORTED GENERAL INFORMATION TO HIS OPERATING LOCATION VIA TELEPHONE. IMMEDIATELY THE FACILITY EMERGENCY RESPONSE TEAM AS WELL AS THE MANAGEMENT TEAM ARRIVED AT THE SITE OF THE VEHICLE ACCIDENT. BFI EMPLOYEES TRAINED IN PROPER EMERGENCY RESPONSE AND SPILL CLEAN-UP PROCEDURES REMEDIED THE SPILL AND TRANSFERRED ALL CONTAINERS FROM THE DAMAGED TRUCK TO A NEW VEHICLE. FOLLOWING THIS INCIDENT, ALL BFI DRIVERS WERE RETRAINED ON DEFENSIVE DRIVING PRACTICES.

column168: AS PREVIOUSLY REPORTED THE INCIDENT TOOK PALACE ON SEPTEMBER 19,1999 AT ABOUT 5:30 PM ON I-10 EASTBOUND IN KENNER NEAR MILE MARKER 224. WHILE TRANSPORTING A 330 GALLON TOTE TANK WITH 32% HYDROCHLORIC ACID, A LEAK DEVELOPED AS RESULT OF AN APPARENTLY DEFECTIVE VALVE/PIPE ASSEMBLY. ABOUT 80 GALLONS OF HCI WERE RELEASED DURING TRANSIT. WHEN THE LEAKING MATERIAL WAS FIRST NOTICED THE TRUCK PULLED OFF THE ROADWAY ONTO SHOULDER JUST PAST THE LOYOLA DRIVE OVER PASS.WHILE THE TRUCK WAS STOPPED THE REMAINDER OF THE TOTE RELEASED INTO A TEMPORARY CONTAINMENT AREA CONSTRUCTED BY OUR DRIVER. SODA ASH WAS USED TO NEUTRALIZED THE HYDROCHLORIC ACID IN THE CONTAINMENT AREA. THE AMOUNT OF HCI RELEASED DOES NOT REPRESENT A REPORTABLE QUANTITY. A THIRD PARTY EMERGENCY RESPONDER (OIL MOP, INC) WAS ALSO CONTRACTED TO ASSIST IN THE CLEAN UP EFFORTS. AFTER THE INCIDENT WAS OVER AND THE CLEAN-UP WAS COMPLETE WE DETERMINED THAT THE VALVE ASSEMBLY ON THE TOTE HAD FAILED CAUSING THE VALVE TO PHISCALLY BREAK OFF FROM THE TOTE DURING TRANSIT. AS A RESULT OF THIS INCIDENT TOTE TANK INSPECTION PROCEDURE HAVE BEEN IMPLEMENTED ALONG WITH A CHANGE IN CHEMICAL TRANSPORTING PROCEDURE TO MINIMIZE OR ELIMINATE THE USE OF TOTE OVER THE ROADWAY.

WHILE UNLOADING AT DESTINATION TERMINAL, IT WAS NOTICED THAT ONE PAIL WAS DENTED IN CENTER AND HAD MINOR LEAKAGE. THE LEAKAGE WAS CONTAINED ON THE TRAILER AND THE PAIL WAS TO ENSURE NO FURTHER LEAKAGE. THE PAIL WAS FORWARDED TO SALVAGE DEPT.

column168: ON THE MORNING OF SEPTEMBER 24 MR DAN LEDO, DRIVER FOR SIERRA CHEMICAL CO., WAS DISPATCHED TO MAKE A TANKER DELIVERY OF SULFURIC ACID TO THE TRACY-CLARK GENERATING PLANT IN PATRICK, NEVADA (THIS FACILITY IS LOCATED APPROXIMATELY 15 MILES FROM OUR SPARKS NEVADA PLANT. MR. LEDO WAS EAST BOUND ON WALTHAM WAY AT THE TIME OF THE INCIDENT. WALTHAM WAY IS SOMEWHAT OF A WINDING "BACKROAD" THAT RUNS THROUGH AN INDUSTRIAL COMPLEX THAT WAS UNDER DEVELOPMENT.  AT THE ACTUAL LOCATION OF THE INCIDENT THE  CLOSEST BUSINESS WAS AROUND A QUARTER MILE AWAY.  THE WEATHER CONDITIONS WAS CLEAR AND DRY WITH THE SUM JUST RISING OVER HE HILL SIDES.  FINDINGS BY THE COUNTY SHERIFF WAS THAT MR. LEDO WAS GOING TOO FAST.  ALTHOUGH THE SPEED WAS NOT INDICATED, THE SHERIFF NOTED THAT THERE WAS SOME 50 FEET OF SKID MARKS ON THE ROAD.  SPEED LIMIT FOR THIS STRETCH OF ROAD WAS 35 MPH. A CONTRIBUTING FACTOR MAY HAVE BEEN THE SUN RISING FROM HE EAST AS THE DRIVER WAS APPROACHING A CURVE IN THE ROAD.  AS SOON AS SIERRA CHEMICAL CO. WAS NOTIFIED OF THE INCIDENT WE DISPATCHED A NUMBER OF OUR HAZWOPER CERTIFIED RESPONDERS, ALONG WITH OUR HAZMAT TRAILER, TO ASSESS THE SITUATION.  OUR RESPONDERS WORKED WITH THE LOCAL AGENCIES UNTIL IT WAS DEEMED THAT NO HAZARD TO THE PUBLIC OR ENVIRONMENT EXISTED AND WAS TURNED OVER TO US TO MITIGATE.  ALONG WITH THE ACTIVITIES OF OUR OWN RESPONDERS, WE CONTRACTED WITH SAFETY KLEEN FOR THE DISPOSAL OF CLEANED UP SOIL.  THE INCIDENT WAS DETERMINED TO BE OPERATOR ERROR.  NO CORRECTIVE ACTION WAS TAKEN AS MR. LEDO QUIT.

ON 9/13/99 AT APPROXIMATELY 0748, EMPLOYEE PETER WEITING REPORTED A HAZARDOUS MATERIALS SPILL TO SUPERVISOR FAUCHER. THE PACKAGE ORIGINATED IN ALLENTOWN, PA, BEEN INSPECTED AT AND MOVED THROUGH THE WILMINGTON, OH HUB, OFF LOADED AT THE NEWTON, MA P&D FACILITY, RUN DOWN A CONVEYER BELT AND PULLED FROM THE CONVEYER BELT BY EMPLOYEE WEITING.  THE PACKAGE WEIGHED 9 LBS AND CONTAINED 2.5 LITERS OF STYRENE MONOMER.  APPROXIMATELY 1 CUP OF MATERIAL WAS SPILLED.  THE MATERIAL WAS IN A GLASS CONTAINER INSIDE A FIBERBOARD BOX.  AFTER FAUCHER WAS INFORMED OF THE SPILL, HE IMMEDIATELY REPORTED IT TO STATION MANAGER DAVE TRABUCCO AND OBTAINED AN ABSORBENT MATERIAL WITH WHICH TO CONTAIN THE SPILL.  SUPV'S PARKINSON AND DINICOLA THEN PROCEEDED TO BAG THE SHIPMENT AND MOVE IT AWAY FROM THE WORKING AREA. MANAGER TRABUCCO, THEN PULLED THE HAZ DECLARATION FROM THE PACKAGE IN ORDER TO OBTAIN INFORMATION ON THE SHIPPER AND THE SUBSTANCE.  A PHONE CALL WAS MADE TO THE SHIPPER'S EMERGENCY NUMBER.  A SECURITY GUARD PICKED UP THE PHONE AND WAS UNABLE TO PROVIDE INFORMATION ON THE SHIPMENT OR AN ALTERNATE NUMBER TO CALL.  CHEMTREC WAS THEN CONTACED TO PROVIDE MSDS INFORMATION WHICH WAS PROMPLTY FAXED TO THE FACILITY.  911 WAS THEN CALLED AND THE BUILDING EVACUATED.  EMERGENCY PERSONEL ATTENDED TO EMPLOYEES WHO COMPLAINED OF RESPITORY DIFFICULTIES, DIZZINESS AND NAUSEA.  FIRE, POLICE, AND AMBULANCE CREWS ARRIVED ON SCENE WITH 8-9 MINUTES OF THE 8:04 911 CALL. APPROXIMATELY 23 EMPLOYEES WERE TREATED AND RELEASED AT 3 AREA HOSPITALS. CLEAN HARBORS WAS NOTIFIED AT 0830 ABOUT THE SPILL AND ARRIVED ON SCENE AT APPROXIMATELY 1030.  CLEANUP CREWS ARRIVED AT APPROXIMATELY 1130 AND COMMENCED CLEANUP ACTIVITIES UNTIL 1400.  ACTION TAKEN TO PREVENT FUTURE OCCURRENCES:  BASED ON CIRCUMSTANCIAL EVIDENCE, THE DRIVER WHO HANDLED TH PACKAGE WAS DISCIPLINED FOR FAILING TO PROPERLY HANDLE HAZARDOUS MATERIAL. AIRBORNE HAS REFUSED TO HANDLE ANY MORE SHIPMENTS CONTAINING THIS SUBSTANCE (STYRENE MONOMER) UNTIL IT HAS INVESTIGATED THE SHIPERS PROCEDURES FOR PACKING THIS MATERIAL.  NO LEAKS OR RESIDUE WERE FOUND IN ANY OTHER TRANSPORTATION CONTAINERS OR ON THE CONVEYER WHICH TRANSPORTED THE PACKAGE FROM THE FREIGHT CONTAINER TO THE EMPLOYEES TRUCKLOAD POSITION. PREVENTATIVE ACTION, IS THEREFORE BEING CONFINED TO HANDLING PROCEDURES, EMPLOYEE AWARENESS AND PACKAGING IMPROVEMENTS BY THE SHIPPER. RECOMMENDATION:  CEASE SHIPPING THIS MATERIAL IN GLASS CONTAINERS AND PACKAGE WITH ABSORBENT MATERIAL IN THE EVENT THAT THE INNER CONTAINER IS RUPTURED.  REVIEW HAZMAT HANDLING PROCEDURES WITH EMPLOYEES.

GATX 70212 WAS FOUND TO BE LEAKING FROM ITS TOP WHILE BEING SWITCHED INTO A YARD TRACK IN GARRETT, IN. THE CAR WAS ISOLATED ON THE WYE TRACK. THE CREW WENT INTO THE YARD OFFICE WHERE CONDUCTOR T.J. WILCOX (ID #516850) COMPLAINED OF NOT FEELING WELL. AFTER REQUESTING TO GO TO HOSPITAL THE REST OF THE CREW REQUESTED THE SAME. TRAINMAN J.W. THOMPSON (ID#373941), ENGINEER P.B. BRUMMETT (ID#199481) AND UTILITY MAN R.L. BLOOM (ID#509949) WERE ALL TAKEN TO THE DEKALB MEMORIAL HOSPITAL IN AUBURN, IN.. ALL FOUR WERE OBSERVED AND RELEASED FROM THE HOSPITAL IMMEDIATELY  FOLLOWING THEIR CHECK-UP. HOWEVER, THE ON CALL DOCTOR ADVISED MR. WILCOX TO "REST" DURING THE DAY OF SEPT. 8, 1999. ALL MEMBERS OF THE CREW COMPLAINED OF HAVING CHEST PAINS, OR HEAVINESS OF BREATHING. ALL CREW MEMBERS HAVE RETURNED TO WORK WITH THE EXCEPTION OF MR. WILCOX WHO IS COMPLAINING OF HAVING HEADACHES, NAUSEA, AND CHEST PAINS. THE CAR WAS INSPECTED BY J. D. CASEY, CSXT MGR.HAZARDOUS MATERIALS AND BRAIN HOLCOMB AND RICHARD TIPPY OF FERGUSON HARBOUR INSTALLED A REPLACEMENT GASKET MADE FROM TEFLON ROPE AND SECURED THE MANWAY. ALL ABOVE ITEMS WERE CORRECTED BY SHELL AND CAR WAS RELEASED TO DESTINATION. MR. DAVE FERGUSON AND THREE OTHER RESPONDERS FROM SHELL, BELVUE, OH. RESPONDED.

column168: ON 9/17/99 JCI DRIVER DAVE DUCHHAM WAS MAKING A DELIVERY OF SODIUM HYPOCHLORITE TO EARTH TECH IN SUSSEX N.J. DAVE HAD ALL CONNECTIONS HOOKED UP VALVES OPEN AND WAS PADDING THE TRAILER WITH AIR. AFTER A FEW MOMENTS THE RUPTURE DISC BLEW RELEASING SOME PRODUCT TO THE GROUND DAVE SHUT THE TRUCK DOWN AND NOTIFIED THE PLANT OPERATOR CALLED JCI. JCI SENT TWO RESPONDERS TO CLEAN UP THE LEAK AND REPAIR THE TRAILER. AFTER THE DISC WAS REPAIRED DAVE ATTEMPTED TO UNLOAD AGAIN  THE RUPTURE DISC BEEN RELEASING MORE PRODUCT. THE DEP OFFICER AT THE SCENE INSTRUCTED THE EMPLOYEES TO WASH DOWN THE SPILL WITH WATER. THE TRAILER WAS RETURNED TO WARWICK AND REPAIRED. A RYDER MECHANIC INSPECTED THE TRAILER AND FOUND THAT THE EMERGENCY BREAK OFF VAVE WAS LEAKING AIR CAUSING THE INTERNAL VALVE TO CLOSE OVERPRESS WRITING THE RUPTURE DISC.

column168: AB7899EXZ, SHIPPER: RAPID, AWB ICT 791695221 CRPI. THIS SHIPMENT WAS PROPERLY MARKED LABELED CERTIFIED AS REGULATED MATERIAL. 01:24. 09/17/99 A ODOR WAS REPORTED AT GATE B 31 OF OUR FACILITY LOCATED AT: ABX AIR INC. 145 HUNTER DRIVE, WILMINGTON , OHIO 45177. THE ODOR WAS REPORTED TOPSIDE ON AIRCRAFT 833AX WITH 4 EMPLOYEES IN CONTACT WITH THE ODOR. HAZARDOUS MATERIALS  COORDINATOR MICHAEL FRYE AND PART TIME HAZMAT SPILL TECHNICIANE MARTIN CLINA AND KIDDER DONNED PERSONNEL PROTECTIVE EQUIPMENT AND RESPONDED TO THE DOOR. UPON ARRIVAL THEY PLACED THE AIR MONITOR INSIDE THE TOPSIDE CARGO AREA, NO ABNORMAL READINGS WERE NOTED. THEY ENTERED TOPSIDE AND BEGAN OFF LOADING THE C CONTAINERS. THE C CONTAINERS WERE BROWN FIBERBOARD BOX SHOWING NO VISIBLE EIGNE OF LEAKAGE ON THE OUTER BOX. THEY OPENED THE BOX AND FOUND 4 INNER METAL CANS WITH SCREW TYPE CLOSURES WITH FIBERBOARD PROTECTIVE COVERING OVER THE CANS, THERE WERE VISIBLE SIGNS OF LEAKAGE ON ONE OF THE FIBERBOARD PROTECTIVE COVERINGS. THE REMAINING 3 SHOWED NO SIGNS OF LEAKAGE. THEY REMOVED THE FIBERBOARD PROTECTIVE COVERING AND FOUND THE INNER METAL CANS CRUSHED AROUND THE BOTTOM AND WAS LEAKING AROUND THE DAMAGED SEAM, THEY REPLACED THE FIBREBOARD PROTECTIVE COVERING AROUND THE METAL CAN, PLACED THE LEAKING VAN INSIDE A PLASTIC BAG WITH ABSORBENT MATERIAL AND PLACED IT BACK INSIDE THE OUTER BOX. THE SHIPMENT WAS SEALED, PLACED INTO 2 PLASTIC BAGS WITH ABSORBENT MATERIAL AND PLACED INSIDE A RECOVERY DRUM. THE DRUMMED IN CONTACT WITH THE ODOR WERE ADVISED WHAT THE SOURCE OF THE ODOR WAS AND RETURNED TO THEIR WORK AREA. NONE OF THE EMPLOYEES IN CLEAR REQUIRED MEDICAL TREATMENT AT THIS TIME. CLEAR OF SCENE: 02:46 COPIES OF THE HAZARDOUS MATERIALS CERTIFICATION AND PACKING SHEET WILL ACCOMPANY THIS REPORT.

column168: OUR DRIVER WAS GOING DOWN A HILL ON A CURVE AT A SPEED OF 50 MPH.  HE DRIFTED OVER THE CENTER LINE INTO THE ONCOMING TRAFFIC LANE.  OUR DRIVER OVERCORRECTED TO THE RIGHT.  THE TRAILER BEGAN TO WHIP, THE TRAILER THEN OVERTURNED ON ITS LEFT SIDE IN THE LEFT LANE.  THE TRAILER SLID DOWN THE ROAD HITTING THE GUARD RAIL.  THE TRAILER SLID AGAINST THE GUARD RAIL FOR APPROXIMATELY 200 FEET, IT THEN SLID ACROSS THE ROAD INTO THE DITCH ON THE RIGHT SIDE OF THE ROAD.  THE TANK WAS PUNCTURED WHEN IT HIT THE GUARD RAIL, RELEASING THE LIQUID ASPHALT INSIDE.  WE WERE NOTIFIED BY THE IDAHO STATE PATROL AT ABOUT 6:30AM, 9/8/99.  WE IMMEDIATELY NOTIFIED THE HAZARDOUS RESPONSE CONTRACTOR AND OUR INSURANCE CARRIER, GREAT WEST CASUALTY.  TIM KASSA OF KASSA INSURANCE SERVICES, INC WAS DISPATCHED BY GREAT WEST CASUALTY TO RESPOND TO THE SCENE.  SAFETY CLASSES FOR THE DRIVERS, EMPHASIZING THE IMPORTANCE OF MAINTAINING A SAFE SPEED AT ALL TIMES.

column168: A PASSENGER (MR. ED STRAND) CHECKED A BAG AND A BOX CURBSIDE AT THE SAN ANTONIO SKYCAP PODIUM FOR FLIGHT ON SWAA FLIGHT #154 FROM SAN ANTONIO TO DALLAS LOVE FIELD (DAL).  WHEN QUESTIONED BY THE SKYCAP, MR. STRAND TOLD HIM THAT HE COULD NOT CARRY MERCURY ABOARD THE AIRCRAFT.  AT THIS POINT MR. STRAND OPENED AND BEGAN TO RUMMAGE THROUGH HIS BAG.  HE TOLD THE SKYCAP THAT HE HAD NOT PACKED THE MERCURY SINCE HE COULDN'T FIND IT IN THE BAG.  THE SKYCAP REPEATED THAT MERCURY WAS NOT ALLOWED ONBOARD THE AIRCRAFT.  MR. STRAND WAS TEN CHECKED IN FOR FLIGHT SINCE HE INDICATED HE DID NOT HAVE THE MATERIAL WITH HIM.  NO SPILLAGE WAS REPORT TO THE DALLAS STATION (MR. STRAND'S DESTINATION), AND THE FLIGHT CONTINUED TO ALBUQUERQUE (ABQ).  ABQ RAMP AGENTS DISCOVERED AND REPORTED THE SPILL DURING THE LOADING OF THE RETURN FLIGHT.  AN EMERGENCY RESPONSE TEAM IN ABQ RESPONDED AND PERFORMED A CLEAN UP OF THE BIN.  A/C MAINTENANCE WAS ALSO DISPATCHED FROM THE PHOENIX MAINTENANCE BASE.  THE DECONTAMINATION TOOK APPROXIMATELY 5 HOURS AND THE INCIDENT WAS COMPLETE.

column168: 09/20/1999 -  A VEHICLE ACCIDENT INVOLVING A C M V OWNED BY JACKSON OIL COMPANY AND A 1997 PONTIAC SUNFIRE OWNED BY MS. ANDREA WALICKI OCCURRED AT MILE MARKER 25, I-24 WEST BOUND DUE TO WEATHER CONDITIONS, SEVERE RAIN. MRS. WALICKI'S VEHICLE HYDROPLANED AND CONTACTED JACKSON OIL COMPANY'S TANKER TRUCK.  THIS CAUSED WRECK AND DAMAGED TO BOTH VEHICLE, FATALITY OF TANKER TRUCK DRIVER AND TOTAL LOSS OF TANKER TRUCK AND TANK TRAILER DUE TO EXPLOSION AND FIRE. FOR RESPONSE AND FOLLOW-UP SEE ATTACHED DOCUMENTS. RESPONDED EMERGENCY.  TRAFFIC TO REPORTED FIRE IN MEDIAN OF INTERSTATE. WHILE EN ROUTE DISPATCH ADVISED SEVERAL CALLS STATING EXPLOSION AT FIRE. E-401 COULD SEE GLOW FROM HWY 41-A.  E-401 REQUESTED TANKER SUPPORT FROM PVFD AND ENGINE AND TANKER FROM ACFD. WHILE EN ROUTE DOWN EASTBOUND SIDE FOUND LARGE FIRE IN MEDIAN AND DOWN SIDES OF WESTBOUND SIDE.  CHEATHAM CO. MEDIC SHUT DOWN EASTBOUND SIDE.  E-401 PROCEEDED DOWN TO TURN AROUND AND BACK UP WESTBOUND SIDE.  UPON ARRIVAL E-401 EST.  COMMAND AND STAGED APPROXIMATELY.  1500 FT. DOWN FROM SCENE.  FIRE NOTED ON BOTH SIDES OF WEST BOUND LANE.  CCSO DEPUTY ON SCENE APPROXIMATELY.  100-150 FT. FROM FIRE.  E-401 TRIED TO OBTAIN INFORMATION FROM DEPUTY ON SCENE.  NO HELPFUL INFORMATION GATHERED WEST BOUND LANE ALSO COMPLETELY SHUT DOWN.  BYSTANDER (TRUCK DRIVER) STATED HE WAS BEHIND THE TRUCK THAT WRECKED AND IT WAS A TRACTOR TRAILER WITH 1203 PLACARDS.  TANKER HAD OBVIOUSLY RUPTURED AND HAD SPILLED FUEL INTO DRAINAGE DITCHES WHICH WERE FULL OF H2O DUE TO WEATHER. HEAVY RAIN CONDITIONS.  ASSISTANCE CHIEF DUNCAN MADE CALL TO HAVE ALL TRUCKS STAGE ON UPPER SIDE OF INCIDENT.  ALL RESPONDING UNITS WERE ADVISED TO APPROACH SCENE ON WEST BOUND LANE COMING EAST BOUND.  WITNESSES ADVISED DRIVER OF TRUCK WAS STILL INSIDE.  WALK AROUND MADE AT SAFE DISTANCE AND DETERMINED TRAILER AND CAB FULLY INVOLVED WITH FIRE. E-12 FOAM 13 REQUESTED FROM N F D FOR POSSIBLE ATTACK.  COMMAND REQUESTED COMMAND BUS FROM CHEAMTHAM CO.  ENGINE CO'S AND TANKERS LINED UP FOR POSSIBLE ATTACK. DETERMINATION MADE UPON ARRIVAL THAT NO POSSIBLE WAY TO SURVIVE IN CAB. COMMAND MADE DECISION ALONG WITH ROB AND CHEATHAM EMA TO LET REMAINDER OF FUEL TO BURN OFF DUE TO WEATHER.  ALSO DIDN'T WANT TO DEAL WITH RUN OFF DUE TO SYCAMORE CREEK APPROXIMATELY 1/2 MILE DOWN HILL.  COMMAND BUS ARRIVED ON SCENE AND SET UP.  CANCELLED E-12 AND FOAM 13 FROM N F D.  ALL OTHER UNITS STAGED SAFE DISTANCE UP HILL.  ENGINE CO SENT TO SOUTH WALKER ROAD, TO INVESTIGATE FIRE AND RUN OFF.  UPON THEIR ARRIVAL, THEY ADVISED ONLY SMALL FIRES LEFT BUT STILL SOME FUEL ON TOP OF H2O IN DRAINAGE DITCH. TEAM ALSO ON SCENE.  OWNER OF TRUCKING COMPANY NOTIFIED AND CLEAN UP CREW NOTIFIED TO COME TO THE SCENE.  FIRE AND BURNING FUEL TRAVELED DOWN HILL THROUGH DRAINAGE DITCH AND THROUGH CULVERT UNDER INTERSTATE INTO DRAINAGE DITCH ON OPPOSITE SIDE OF SOUTH WALER ROAD.  APPROXIMATE 1/4 TO 1/2 MILE FROM ACCIDENT SCENE. NO OTHER APPARENT FIRE HAZARDS DUE TO RAIN.  COMMAND SENT B-421

AT APPROXIMATELY 02:10 HRS ON FRIDAY THE TENTH DAY OF SEPTEMBER 1999. MGR RODABOUGH WAS NOTIFIED BY RMCC OF A SPILL AT GREEN RIVER WYO. MGR RODABOUGH DEPARTED FOR GREEN RIVER AT APPROXIMATELY 03:00 HRS AND ARRIVED AT 0535 HRS. UPON ARRIVAL MGR RODABOUGH MADE CONTACT WITH MR CHUCK THOMPSON AND MR MIKE KNEZOVICH BOTH FROM SFI INC. OF GREEN RIVER A FERTILIZER PRODUCER IN THAT AREA, THEY HAD APPARENTLY BEEN CALLED TO ASSIST WITH THE TANKCAR AND WERE IN FACT IN THE PROCESS OR THE TRANSLOADING THE CONTENTS OF THE LEAKING CAR GATX 52822 INTO TANKCAR UTLX 13376. THE TRANSLOAD OPERATION WAS COMPLETED AT 0900 HRS. THE EMPTY CAR WAS WASHED OUT AND STENCIL."LEAKER DO NOT LOAD". BOTH CARS WERE RELEASED UTLX 13376 TO DESTINATION AND GATX 52822 TO BE REPAIRED. THE ACID WAS PUDDLED UNDER THE CAR AND BETWEEN 30TH AND 31ST RAILS AND RAN NORTH  AND SOUTH FOR 80 FEET. THE CONTRACTOR SFI HAD USED SODA ASH FROM A GONDOLA CAR THAT HAD BEEN SPOTTED FOR THAT PURPOSE TO CONTROL THE FLOW OF THE ACID  AND TO HELP IN THE NEUTRALIZATION PROCESS. CONTRACTOR HB&R HAD RESPONDED WITH A VAC TRUCK AND OPERATOR. THE VAC TRUCK WAS USED TO REMEDITATE THE SITE, THE ACID WAS NEUTRALIZED WITH SODA ASH AND THE SITE WAS CLEANED. THE TRUCK WAS ABLE TO REMOVE ALL THE SPILLED PRODUCT AND MOST OF THE CONTAMINATED SOILS. THE SPILL WAS COVERED WITH SODA ASH AND TE ENTIRE SITE WAS CLEAN FILL. THE TANKCAR WAS INSPECTED BY MR BYRON EKLUND THE CAR AND DERRICK FORMAN AND THERE WAS NO EVIDENCE OF ROUGH HANDLING, IT APPEARS THAT THE TANK SIMPLY FAILED, RESULTING IN THE SPILL.

column168: DEAN C COOPER MANAGER CHEMICAL TRANSPORTATION SAFETY RECEIVED A CALL FROM RMCC REPORTING A LEAKING TANK CAR AT THE EAST YARD, CITY OF COMMERCE, EAST LOS ANGELES, CALIFORNIA. DEVELOPING THE ABOVE TANK CAR WAS BEING MOVED IN BOWL #16 TRACK CAUSING PRODUCT TO ESCAPE FROM THE TOP PORTION OF THE CAR, AND AS THE PRODUCT WAS HITTING THE GROUND, SMALL FIRES WERE ERUPTING. THE FIRE DEPARTMENT WAS ON SITE AND HAD EXTINGUISHED THE FIRES AND THE PRODUCT WAS IDENTIFIED AS THE SOURCE OF THE FIRES, THE HAZARDOUS MATERIALS TEAM HAD BEEN NOTIFIED TO INVESTIGATE THE LEAK.MANAGER COOPER DRIVE TO THE EAST YARD AND MET WITH THE COUNTY OF LOS ANGELES FIRE DEPARTMENT HAZARDOUS MATERIALS TEAM AND REPRESENTATIVES OF THE L.A. COUNTY HEALTH HAZ MAT GROUP. BASED UPON INFORMATION DEVELOPED BY THE HAZARDOUS MATERIALS TEAM DEVELOPED THE SOURCE OF THE LEAK TO BE FROM A BLOWN FRANGIBLE DISC IN THE SAFETY VENT. UPON REMOVING THE BURST FRANGIBLE DISC DEVELOPED A LIKE TYPE REPLACEMENT DISC WAS NOT ON HAND. THE SAFETY VENT WAS SECURED WITH A TEMPORARY CLOSURE TO PROTECT THE PRODUCT AND ALLOW THE CAR TO BE MOVED TO A SECURE LOCATION. CONTACT WAS MADE WITH THE DEGAUSS EMERGENCY RESPONSE COORDINATOR IN MOBILE,ALABAMA WHO ARRANGED TO OVERNIGHT A REPLACEMENT DISC. ONCE THE REPLACEMENT DISC WAS RECEIVED THE TEMPORARY CLOSURE WAS REMOVED AND THE NEW DISC INSTALLED. THE CAR WAS THEN RELEASED FOR MOVEMENT ONTO THE CONSIGNEE. IT APPEARS THAT THIS NEW CAR WAS SUBJECTED TO AN OVER SPEED IMPACT, WHICH CAUSED THE LIQUID TO SURGE UP THROUGH THE SAFETY VENT AND BURST THE FRANGIBLE DISC. NOTIFICATIONS WERE MADE TO CHEMTREC FOR REPORTING PURPOSES AND THE SHIPPER AS INFORMATION.

column168: ON 9/27/99 2:48 A SPILL WAS REPORTED IN BUILDING 207 OF OUR SORT FACILITY LOCATED AT ABX AIR INC., 145 HUNTER DR, WILMINGTON, OHIO 45177. PART TIME SPILL TECHNICIANS MIRANDA SOUTH AND PAUL SCHMIDT DONNED PROTECTIVE EQUIPMENT AND RESPONDED TO THE SPILL. UPON ARRIVAL THEY FOUND A CLEAR C CONTAINER WITH A BROWN FIREBOARD BOX INSIDE WITH VISIBLE SIGNS OF LEAKAGE ON THE OUTER PACKAGE. THEY TESTED THE LEAKING LIQUID PH READING 7. THE BOX WAS MARKED LABELED AND CERTIFIED AS THE FOLLOWING REGULATED MATERIAL. THE BOX HAS ORIENTATION ARROWS AND MARKINGS AS FOLLOWS INNER PACKAGES COMPLY WITH PRESCRIBED SPECIFICATIONS, LIQUID IN PLASTIC, DO NOT CUT OR CRUSH, THIS END UP. THEY OPENED THE BOX AND FOUND AN INNER FIREBOARD BOX, THIS BOX WAS MARKED AND LABELED IN THE FOLLOWING MANNER. LIQUID IN PLASTIC  DO NOT CRUSH OR CUT THIS END UP. THEY OPENED THE INNER BOX AND FOUND 4-8 OUNCE PLASTIC BOTTLES WERE  NOT SECURE CAUSING THE LEAKAGE OF APPROX 1/4 OUNCE TOTAL OF ALL FOUR PRODUCTS. THEY SECURED THE CLOSURE ON THE BOTTLES RESEALED THE INNER AND OUTER BOXES, PLACED THE SHIPMENT INSIDE TWO PLASTIC BAGS WITH ABSORBENT MATERIAL AND PLACED THE BAGGED SHIPMENT INSIDE A SALVAGE DRUM FOR TRANSPORT ONTO DESTINATION.  THE C CONTAINER WAS CLEANED BEFORE IT WAS PLACED INTO THE CONTAINER. THE CERTIFICATION FOR DANGEROUS GOODS WILL ACCOMPANY THIS REPORT.

column168: DEAN C COOPER MANAGER CHEMICAL TRANSPORTATION SAFETY WAS CONTACTED BY ICTF SECURITY FORCES REPORTING A LEAKING CONTAINER. MANAGER COOPER DROVE TO THE ICTF AND LOCATED THE ABOVE CONTAINER IN 805E, STALL #345. A SMALL POOL OF LIQUID (LESS THAN 1 GALLON) WAS NOTED ON THE PAVEMENT BELOW THE CENTER OF THE CONTAINER WHERE THE PRODUCT WAS LEAKING THROUGH THE FLOORING. THE CONTAINER WAS DIAOERED IN ORDER TO MOVE IT TO THE CONTAINMENT AREA AT THE CUSTOMER DOCK. UPON OPENING THE REAR DOORS, OBSERVED THE LANDING TO BE 30 GALLON POLY DRUMS STRETCH WRAPPED TO PALLETS AND DOUBLE STACKED IN THE CONTAINER. A 3 FOOT VOID AT THE REAR OF THE LANDING WAS SECURE WITH BLOCKING AND BRACING WHICH APPEARED TO MEET THE AAR BOE 6C STANDARD. AS THE DRUMS WERE SMALLER THAN THE NORMAL 55 GALLON DRUMS THERE WAS A VOID DOWN THE CENTER OF THE CONTAINER, WHICH THE SHIPPER HAD COMPENSATED FOR BY UTILIZING DID BAGS. THIS IS NOT RECOMMENDED PROTOCOL TO SECURE DRUMS FROM HAZARDOUS MATERIALS TRANSPORTED BY RAIL NOR IS IT AN APPROVED METHOD PER THE AAR BOE6C. 2 OF THE 3 DID BAGS DEFLATED DURING TRANSIT WHICH ALLOWED THE PALLETS TO SHIFT. CONTACT WITH THE SHIPPER, ROHM HAAS, BAYPORT TEXAS WAS MADE AND THEY WERE ADVISED OF THE CONDITION OF THE LANDING WHICH WOULD REQUIRE REMOVAL TO INSPECT THE SUSPECT DRUM(S). ARRANGEMENT WERE MADE TO OFF LOAD THE CONTENTS AND INSPECT THE DRUMS FOR DAMAGE.NEAR THE CENTER OF THE LOAD ONE FLOOR LOADED PALLET ON THE LEAFT SIDE WAS FOUND TO HAVE A SINGLE DRUM LEAKING. A NAIL HEAD FROM THE PALLET WAS ELEVATED AND HAD WORN THROUGH THE BOTTOM OF THE POLY DRUM. AN ESTIMATED 10 GALLONS OF PRODUCT WAS LOST FROM THE DRUM. THE DRUM WAS PATCHED AND PLACED INTO AN OVER PACK FOR SECUREMENT. THE PRODUCT RESIDUE ON THE FLOOR WAS CLEANED AND THE LANDING PLACED BACK INTO ORIGINAL CONTAINER. THE DAMAGE DRUM WAS ALSO PLACED BACK WITH THE LADING FOR DELIVERY TO THE LOCAL CONSIGNEE PER THE SHIPPER REQUEST.NOTIFICATION WERE MADE TO CHEMTREC FOR REPORTING PURPOSES AND THE SHIPPER FOR CORRECTIVE ACTION.

column168: DEAN C COOPER MANAGER CHEMICAL TRANSPORTATION SAFETY WAS CONTACTED BY P & O CONTAINER LINES, REPORTING LEAKING CONTAINER AT THE YARD. MANAGER COOPER DROVE TO THE EAST YARD CITY OF COMMERCE, CALIFORNIA LOCATED THE ABOVE CONTAINER AND FOUND NO VISIBLE SIGN OF LIQUID DRIPPING HOWEVER THERE WAS A STRONG PRESENCE OF ODORS. THE CONTAINER WAS MOVED TO LOT #6 WHERE IT COULD BE ISOLATED AND INSPECTED. UPON OPENING THE REAR DOORS NOTED THE LADING TO CONSIST OF 55 GALLON POLY DRUMS. THE FLOOR LOADED DRUMS HAD A 6 FOOT VOID BETWEEN THE DRUMS AND THE REAR OF THE CONTAINER AND THE TOP LOADED DRUM HAD A 12 FOOT VOID BETWEEN THE DRUMS AND THE REAR OF THE CONTAINER. THERE WAS NO BILEVEL SEPARATION BETWEEN THE LAYERS OF DRUMS AND THE BLOCKING AND BRACING CONSISTED OF 2X4 LUMBER. THIS IS NOT A RECOMMENDED PROTOCOL FOR THE TRANSPORTATION OF HAZARDOUS MATERIALS FOR RAIL NOR IS IT AN APPROVED METHOD PER THE AAR BOE 6C. DURING THE REMOVAL PROCESS IT WAS NOTED THAT A MAJORITY OF THE DRUMS HAD A TEA SPOON OF PRODUCT ON THE TOPS OF THE DRUMS. DEVELOPED THE DRUM BUNGS WERE LOOSE, ALLOWING THE PRODUCT TO BYPASS THE BUNGS DURING TRANSPORTATION. ALL THE DRUMS WERE INSPECTED AND THE BUNGS TIGHTENED. THE LOCAL REPRESENTATIVES OF THE SHIPPER PROVIDED REPLACEMENT DUST COVERS FOR THE DRUMS WHICH WERE APPLIED ONCE THE BUNGS WERE SECURED. THE ENTIRE LADING WENT BACK INTO THE ORIGINAL CONTAINER FOR MOVEMENT ONTO THE CONSIGNEE. NOTIFICATIONS WERE MADE TO CHEMTREC FOR REPORTING PURPOSE AND THE SHIPPER FOR CORRECTIVE ACTION.

AT 0930 EST VEHICLE ENTERED PORT OF ENTRY-GALLUP, N.M. THE VEHICLE WAS TRANSPORTING 88 DRUMS OF PRODUCT IDENTIFIED INTERNAL 12 FROM LOS ANGELES, CA. TO CALVERT CITY, KY.  ONE DRUM HAD FAILED.  PORT OF ENTRY & RT. 118 WAS CLOSED FROM 0930 EST UNTIL 0200 EST. NRC WAS NOTIFIED @ 0949 EST - REPORT #499516.  RESPONSE TEAM WAS DISPATCHED FROM ALBUQUERQUE.  THE LEAKING DRUM WAS PLACED INTO A SALVAGE DRUM AT 0600 EST. ONE OTHER DRUM WAS PLACED INTO A SALVAGE DRUM DUE TO QUESTIONABLE INTEGRITY.  ALL MATERIALS USED TO CLEAN UP LEAK WERE PLACED IN SALVAGE DRUM.  APPROXIMATELY 2 LITERS OF MATERIAL HAD LEAKED ONTO FLOOR BUT DID NOT LEAVE TRAILER.  ARE INVESTIGATION IS ONGOING IN THE COMPANY AND DRIVERS ARE UNDERGOING REFRESHER TRAINING.

column62: Rollover Accident; Vehicular Crash or Accident Damage
column168: JOE BRYSON WAS HAULING 5,000 GALLONS OF 28% HCL TO A COASTAL LOCATION FOR A JOB THE NEXT DAY, HE WAS THE 2ND. TRUCK IN CONVOY. JOE AND THE OTHER TRANSPORT HAD STOPPED AT THE ALTOMONT STORE ABOUT A HALF-MILE FROM LOCATION TO WAIT FOR THE CONVOY LEADER TO GIVE THEM THE ALL CLEAR BEFORE  GOING IN TO LOCATION. TONY HOLT GAVE THEM THE ALL CLEAR; JOE DROVE TO THE TURN ON TO THE LEASE ROAD GOING FROM PAVED ROAD TO DIRT. THE PAVED ROAD HAD WATER DITCHES ON BOTH SIDES OF THE ROAD. JOE WAS MAKING HIS TURN (RIGHT TURN) ON TO THE DIRT ROAD HE WAS LOOKING IN HIS MIRROR SEEN THAT HE HAD ENOUGH ROOM AND KEPT GOING. JOE HAD 4 TO 6 FEET OF CLEARANCE FROM THE EDGE OF THE CULVERT WHEN THE CULVERT COLLAPSED CAUSING  THE TRUCK TO ROLL ONTO ITS RIGHT SIDE. AT THIS TIME THE TRUCK KNOCKED DOWN A POWER POLE AND COLLAPSED A 6-FT FENCE AND LANDED AGAINST A SMALL TREE. THE SAFETY DEVICES ON THE DOME LIDS DID NOT ALLOW MORE THAN ABOUT 2 GALLONS OF ACID TO ESCAPE FROM THE TRANSPORT. (AND ONLY THE FRONT DOME LID DID THIS. THE REAR DUELS AND ABOUT 1/3 OF THE TRANSPORT WAS IN THE MAIN CREEK BED. THE PH OF THE WATER WAS TESTED EVERY 10 MINUTES TO MAKE SURE THERE WAS NO CONTAMINATION OF THE WATER, WHICH THERE WAS NONE.
